// ─── READ ALOUD (30 items) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
export const readAloudItems = [
  { id: 'ra-001', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The human brain contains approximately 86 billion neurons, each forming thousands of connections with other neurons. This complex network enables everything from basic reflexes to sophisticated reasoning and creativity. Scientists continue to discover new ways in which neural plasticity allows the brain to reorganize itself in response to learning and experience, suggesting that intelligence is far more malleable than once believed.' },
  { id: 'ra-002', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Climate change represents one of the most pressing challenges of the twenty-first century. Rising global temperatures are causing glaciers to retreat, sea levels to rise, and extreme weather events to become more frequent and intense. Without significant reductions in greenhouse gas emissions, scientists warn that irreversible damage to ecosystems and human communities will occur within decades.' },
  { id: 'ra-003', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The development of artificial intelligence has transformed industries ranging from healthcare to finance. Machine learning algorithms can now diagnose diseases, predict market fluctuations, and compose music with remarkable accuracy. However, concerns about algorithmic bias, privacy, and the displacement of human workers remain significant ethical challenges that policymakers and technologists must address together.' },
  { id: 'ra-004', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Language acquisition in early childhood follows a remarkably consistent sequence across all cultures. Infants first distinguish phonemes, then babble, produce single words, and eventually combine words into sentences. Researchers have found that the quantity and quality of language input from caregivers directly influences the speed and sophistication with which children develop their linguistic abilities.' },
  { id: 'ra-005', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Photosynthesis is the process by which plants convert sunlight into chemical energy stored as glucose. This reaction occurs in the chloroplasts, where chlorophyll absorbs light energy and uses it to combine carbon dioxide and water. The oxygen released as a byproduct is essential for most life on Earth, making photosynthesis the foundation of nearly all food chains.' },
  { id: 'ra-006', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Urbanization is accelerating at an unprecedented rate, with more than half of the global population now living in cities. This shift creates enormous opportunities for economic development and cultural exchange, but also generates serious challenges including traffic congestion, air pollution, inadequate housing, and pressure on water supplies. Sustainable urban planning is therefore critical to ensuring liveable cities for future generations.' },
  { id: 'ra-007', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The theory of evolution by natural selection, first proposed by Charles Darwin in 1859, fundamentally changed humanity\'s understanding of life on Earth. Darwin demonstrated that species change over generations as individuals with advantageous traits survive and reproduce at higher rates. This simple yet powerful mechanism explains the extraordinary diversity of organisms found across all ecosystems on the planet.' },
  { id: 'ra-008', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Quantum mechanics describes the behaviour of matter and energy at the atomic and subatomic scale, where classical physics breaks down. Particles can exist in multiple states simultaneously, a phenomenon known as superposition, and can become entangled such that the state of one instantly influences another regardless of the distance between them. These counterintuitive properties underpin technologies including lasers, transistors, and quantum computers.' },
  { id: 'ra-009', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The global food system faces the monumental task of feeding a population projected to reach ten billion by 2050. Meeting this demand sustainably requires not only increasing agricultural productivity but also dramatically reducing food waste, shifting dietary patterns towards plant-based foods, and protecting soil health. Innovations in precision farming, vertical agriculture, and biotechnology offer promising avenues for achieving food security.' },
  { id: 'ra-010', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Ocean acidification, caused by the absorption of excess atmospheric carbon dioxide, is threatening marine ecosystems worldwide. As seawater becomes more acidic, the shells and skeletons of corals, molluscs, and other calcifying organisms weaken and dissolve. Scientists warn that the loss of coral reefs alone would devastate marine biodiversity and remove a critical buffer protecting coastlines from storm surges.' },
  { id: 'ra-011', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The Renaissance was a period of profound cultural and intellectual transformation that swept across Europe between the fourteenth and seventeenth centuries. Inspired by rediscovered classical texts, scholars and artists challenged medieval assumptions about humanity\'s place in the cosmos. Figures such as Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Galileo exemplified the era\'s spirit of curiosity, empirical inquiry, and the celebration of human potential.' },
  { id: 'ra-012', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Sleep is far more than a period of rest. During sleep, the brain consolidates memories, flushes out metabolic waste products through the glymphatic system, and restores emotional regulation. Chronic sleep deprivation is associated with increased risks of obesity, cardiovascular disease, depression, and cognitive decline. Public health experts increasingly advocate for policies that prioritise adequate sleep as a cornerstone of wellbeing.' },
  { id: 'ra-013', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Microplastics, defined as plastic fragments smaller than five millimetres, have been detected in every ocean, from polar ice caps to the deepest trenches. These particles enter the marine environment through the degradation of larger plastic waste and from synthetic textiles washed in domestic laundry. Their impact on marine organisms and, ultimately, human health through seafood consumption is an active area of scientific investigation.' },
  { id: 'ra-014', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The Industrial Revolution, which began in Britain during the late eighteenth century, fundamentally restructured economies and societies across the globe. Steam-powered machinery replaced manual labour in textile mills, iron foundries, and coal mines, enabling mass production on an unprecedented scale. The resulting social upheaval created new urban working classes, inspired labour movements, and laid the groundwork for modern capitalism.' },
  { id: 'ra-015', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Vaccination has been one of the most effective public health interventions in human history. By introducing weakened or inactivated pathogens, vaccines train the immune system to mount rapid responses against future infections. The eradication of smallpox and the near-elimination of polio demonstrate what coordinated global vaccination programmes can achieve, saving millions of lives and preventing immeasurable suffering.' },
  { id: 'ra-016', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The water cycle, also known as the hydrological cycle, describes the continuous movement of water through Earth\'s systems. Water evaporates from oceans, lakes, and rivers, rises into the atmosphere, condenses into clouds, and falls as precipitation. It then flows across land surfaces into rivers and aquifers, eventually returning to the ocean. Human activities including deforestation and groundwater extraction are disrupting this cycle in significant ways.' },
  { id: 'ra-017', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The emergence of the internet has redefined how human beings communicate, access information, and conduct commerce. Within a single generation, an interconnected global network has disrupted established industries, enabled new forms of democratic participation, and accelerated scientific collaboration. Yet the digital divide — the gap between those with and without reliable internet access — remains a critical barrier to equitable participation in modern economies.' },
  { id: 'ra-018', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Biodiversity refers to the variety of life on Earth at all its levels, from genes to ecosystems. Healthy ecosystems with high biodiversity are more resilient to environmental disturbances and provide essential services including pollination, water purification, and carbon sequestration. The current rate of species extinction, estimated to be one thousand times the natural background rate, is driven primarily by habitat destruction, overexploitation, and climate change.' },
  { id: 'ra-019', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Cognitive biases are systematic patterns of deviation from rational thought that influence human judgement and decision-making. Confirmation bias, for instance, causes people to favour information that supports their existing beliefs while discounting contradictory evidence. Understanding these biases is crucial in fields ranging from medicine to law and economics, as they can lead to costly errors when unchecked.' },
  { id: 'ra-020', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Antibiotic resistance is emerging as one of the gravest threats to global health in the coming decades. The overuse and misuse of antibiotics in both human medicine and agriculture has accelerated the evolution of drug-resistant bacteria. If current trends continue, common infections that were once easily treatable may become life-threatening, reversing decades of medical progress and placing enormous strain on healthcare systems worldwide.' },
  { id: 'ra-021', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Architecture is the art and science of designing and constructing the built environment. Beyond providing shelter and functional space, great architecture shapes how communities experience their surroundings and expresses the cultural values of its era. From the geometric precision of ancient Egyptian temples to the glass-and-steel towers of contemporary cities, buildings serve as enduring records of human ingenuity and aspiration.' },
  { id: 'ra-022', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The human genome, comprising approximately three billion base pairs of DNA, encodes the genetic instructions for the development and functioning of the human body. Advances in sequencing technology have made it possible to read an individual\'s entire genome quickly and affordably, opening new frontiers in personalised medicine. Scientists can now identify genetic variants associated with inherited diseases and develop targeted therapies accordingly.' },
  { id: 'ra-023', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Renewable energy sources including solar, wind, and hydroelectric power are transforming the global energy landscape. The cost of solar photovoltaic panels has fallen by more than ninety percent over the past decade, making clean electricity competitive with fossil fuels in many markets. Transitioning to a fully renewable energy system requires not only technological innovation but also substantial investment in electricity grids and energy storage.' },
  { id: 'ra-024', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The Silk Road was not a single road but an extensive network of trade routes connecting China with Central Asia, the Middle East, and Europe. For over a millennium, merchants transported silk, spices, porcelain, and glassware along these routes, facilitating not only commercial exchange but also the spread of religions, technologies, and artistic styles across vast distances and diverse civilisations.' },
  { id: 'ra-025', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Mindfulness, rooted in ancient Buddhist contemplative traditions, has gained widespread acceptance in Western medicine and psychology. Research shows that regular mindfulness practice can reduce symptoms of anxiety, depression, and chronic pain by teaching individuals to observe their thoughts and sensations without judgement. Many hospitals and schools now offer mindfulness programmes as part of comprehensive approaches to mental and physical health.' },
  { id: 'ra-026', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The discovery of CRISPR-Cas9 gene editing technology has revolutionised biological research and medicine. By allowing scientists to precisely cut and modify DNA sequences, CRISPR opens possibilities for curing genetic diseases, developing disease-resistant crops, and even potentially eliminating certain hereditary conditions from future generations. However, the ethical implications of germline editing — changes that are heritable — demand careful societal debate.' },
  { id: 'ra-027', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'The psychology of motivation distinguishes between intrinsic motivation, driven by internal rewards such as interest and satisfaction, and extrinsic motivation, driven by external incentives such as money or grades. Research consistently shows that intrinsic motivation produces deeper learning and greater creativity, whereas excessive reliance on external rewards can undermine genuine engagement. These findings have profound implications for education, management, and public policy.' },
  { id: 'ra-028', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Deep-sea exploration has revealed ecosystems of extraordinary diversity thriving under conditions once considered incompatible with life. Hydrothermal vents on the ocean floor support communities of tube worms, shrimp, and microorganisms that derive energy from chemical reactions rather than sunlight. These discoveries have expanded scientists\' understanding of where life can exist and have implications for the search for life on other planets.' },
  { id: 'ra-029', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Supply chains have become increasingly complex and globalised over the past half century. A single consumer product may incorporate raw materials from a dozen countries, processed and assembled by workers across multiple continents before reaching the end consumer. While this global integration has reduced costs and expanded consumer choice, the COVID-19 pandemic exposed the fragility of these interdependencies when disruptions occur simultaneously in multiple regions.' },
  { id: 'ra-030', type: 'read-aloud', section: 'speaking', prepTime: 40, speakTime: 40,
    passage: 'Ancient Rome\'s legal system laid the foundations for legal traditions that continue to shape modern law across much of the world. Roman jurists developed principles of property rights, contract enforcement, and criminal procedure that were remarkably sophisticated. Codified in the Corpus Juris Civilis under Emperor Justinian, Roman law was rediscovered in medieval Europe and profoundly influenced the civil law systems of continental Europe and their colonial descendants.' },
]

